(2093, 1, '2014-10-26 01:45:30', '2014-10-26 01:45:30', '<h1>Our History</h1>\r\nIn recent years, erasure and gate-keeping Black creativity and the Black narrative in publishing has become a hot topic. Here at <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span>, we understand that both these acts are due to a lack of Black cultural institutions. The lack of cultural institution allows the Black narrative to be easily misconstrued, marginalized, replaced, and commercialized by the ruling racial class. The result leads Blacks to beg the ruling racial class, which benefit from the aforementioned acts (and created the situations for these acts to take root in the first place), for permission to create stories that reflect our true selves. A permission that will never come. And we at <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> don''t ask for permission.\r\n\r\n<h1>Our Mission</h1>\r\n<span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> is an online literary magazine that features young Black protagonists (ages of 13-19), from Black writers who are often ignored in mainstream and independent publishing. <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> is committed to the ideal that the Black narrative is also the default and will lead to validation, racial pride, and ultimately cultural protection.\r\n', 'About Us <i class="fa fa-users"></i>', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'about-us', '', '', '2014-11-06 16:34:34', '2014-11-06 16:34:34', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?page_id=2093', 0, 'page', '', 0),
(2094, 1, '2014-10-26 01:19:28', '2014-10-26 01:19:28', 'The African Review is an online literary magazine featuring young black protagonists from the ages of 13-19 from black writers. The goal is to strengthen the black voice in young adult and middle grade fiction and expose young readers to the diversity of the black experience. We hope to aid the black youth to see themselves as the default with the exceptional work of a newer generation and give a platform to those that have been ignored in the past from mainstream and independent markets.\r\n\r\nTeens are also encouraged to write stories, providing they are high quality. We are seeking to publish the work of young, gifted, and black teens.\r\n\r\nSimultaneous submissions are permitted. Please notify us immediately if the work has been accepted elsewhere. We prefer work that has not been previously published. The Africana Review asks for non-exclusive electronic rights.\r\n', 'About Us', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2093-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-26 01:19:28', '2014-10-26 01:19:28', '', 2093, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2094', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2095, 1, '2014-10-26 01:21:20', '2014-10-26 01:21:20', 'Founded in Chicago by Adlyn Morrison in 2015, The Africana Review was a response to the lack of creative black voices in Young Adult Literature and with a hope that blacks could own and reinforce their culture using their voices. In giving a platform to the good writers and poets shut out from the mainstream and indie (i.e. white owned) literary communities, The Africana Review seeks to welcome those that reveal complexity of black life.\r\nWe accept submissions February 13-15th, May 13-15th, August 13-15th, and November 13-15th. We consider each submission for all upcoming issues, regardless of theme. If you wish to be considered for a particular theme, please make note in your cover letter. \r\nThe Africana Review has announced the summer theme of Fight to the Death. We are looking for fiction, essays, and poems about Fighting to the Death with people, animals, organizations, institutions, physical locations—the theme is open to interpretation.\r\n', 'About Us', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2093-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-26 01:21:20', '2014-10-26 01:21:20', '', 2093, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2095', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
