(2124, 1, '2014-10-26 02:15:05', '2014-10-26 02:15:05', '<h1>The Afrikana Review Theme Issues</h1>\r\n\r\nSubmissions are accepted February 13-15th, May 13-15th, August 13-15th, and November 13-15th. We consider each submission for all upcoming issues, regardless of theme. If you wish to be considered for a particular theme, please make note in your cover letter.\r\n\r\n<span class="afrikana red">The Afrikana Review</span> <strong class="red">has announced the summer theme of Fight to the Death. We are looking for fiction, essays, and poems about Fighting to the Death with people, animals, organizations, institutions, physical locations—the theme is open to interpretation. </strong>\r\n\r\nGifted teens are <em>highly</em> encouraged to send stories, providing they are high quality.\r\n\r\nSimultaneous submissions are permitted. Please notify us immediately if the work has been accepted elsewhere. We prefer work that has not been previously published. <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> asks for non-exclusive electronic rights.\r\n\r\n<h2>Formatting</h2>\r\nFormatting Standard manuscript format is required, 12-point font (Times or Times New Roman), double-spaced with one-inch margins all around. Please put the page number, your last name, and title of entry in the top right corner of each page. Attachments are required and MUST be labeled with the title of your piece. Please send your work in a PDF. Please do not send your work in the body of your email. Send submissions to: edior@convenientstore.com. Subject line in ALL CAPS: SUBMISSION. YOU MUST INCLUDE A COVER EMAIL WITH THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A brief summary of your narrative (3 sentences) if you have one. </li>\r\n<li>A brief bio (no more than forty words, please.). </li>\r\n<li>No pieces that are previously published accepted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you would like to illustrate for <span class="afrikana">The Afrikan Review</span>, please send us three samples of your artwork or a link to your portfolio page along with a bio letter.\r\n\r\nWould you like to illustrate your own story? It’s perfectly find to send an illustrated story by yourself or a friend. If we like the story and the illustrations, we will publish them both. If we like the story but not the illustrations, we will find our own illustrator for your story. If we like the illustrations but not the story, we will contact you to see if you’d like to become an <span class="afrikana">Afrikan Review</span> illustrator. Remember to send copies of your artwork, not originals.\r\n\r\n<h2>Poetry</h2>\r\nWe at <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> prefer free-verse poems over rhyming poems. If you write rhyming poems, you should probably send it to a different publisher. At <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span>. We are seeking poetry that:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Engages with the unfamiliar and jarring</li>\r\n<li>Articulates and provokes our starkest emotions</li>\r\n<li>Offers the reader unexpected modes of interaction</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\nPlease submit 3-5 poems not exceeding 1500 words, in one document.\r\n\r\n<h2>Flash Fiction</h2>\r\nAll flash fiction and flash nonfiction should be under 300 words.\r\n\r\n<h2>Prose Fiction or Nonfiction</h2>\r\nWe are looking for prose that is arresting, that fearlessly disrupts the story on black teens and children. Stories that grips our throats. Stories that break our hearts. Stories that blows our mind. We want the unexpected, prose that extends the plight of boundaries blackness in form, language, or narrative. \r\n\r\nAll other forms: No more than 2 pieces not exceeding 5,000 words or twenty pages.\r\n\r\n<h2>Graphic Novels or Comics</h2>\r\nFor this type of submission, we request that you submit in .jpg, .tiff or .pdf format.\r\nQuery before sending in book reviews, interviews, and literary criticism. (editor@convenient.com) \r\n\r\n<h2>What Are Some Stories Not Allowed?</h2>\r\nWe are not looking for the stereotypical stories that have been rehashed repeatedly in the media when it comes to the black youth. We ask for the following subjects not be the main attribute of the protagonist:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gangster</li>\r\n<li>Drug dealer</li>\r\n<li>Teen parent</li>\r\n<li>Prisoner</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\nWe ask that if your story does have a common narrative in media (poverty, abuse, violence, prison, slavery, colonialism, racism), it cannot be the focus of the story. If it does, we suggest a different publisher.\r\n\r\n<h2>Can A Historical Figure Be a Protagonist?</h2>\r\nWhile we are not against historical figures in your stories, they just cannot be the protagonist. We are looking for fresh new protagonists that drive the story forward.\r\n\r\n<h2>Can The Protagonist Be Mixed Race Heritage?</h2>\r\n<span class="red"> No, the protagonist cannot be racially mixed and neither can the parents, if the protagonist has any. If you are sending a illustration, the protagonist must look visibly Afrikan. When we mean “visibly Afrikan,” we mean there can be no doubt of the character''s racial makeup to <strong>our readers and us at <span class="afrikana">Afrikana</span></strong>. We will leave this up to you judge what is considered “visibly Afrikan.” Please be aware that your ideal may not be others.</span>\r\n\r\n<h2>What If The Protagonist Is Of Another Species?</h2>\r\nIf the protagonist is of another species, that is fine, however, if the species resembles human beings (like Superman for example), they must look “visibly Afrikan.”\r\n\r\n<h2>Can The Protagonist Be From Another Country Outside The United States?</h2>\r\nYes, they can be. We understand that the majority of Black teens reside outside the United States. We would love to hear stories from protagonist of different countries. Feel free to sprinkle in your native language (provided with a glossary).\r\n\r\n<h2>What Stories Are You Looking For?</h2>\r\nHere at Afrikana Review we are looking for stories from these genres:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Action/Adventure</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Coming-of-Age</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Drama</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Fantasy</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Horror</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Mystery</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Psychological</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Tragedy</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Science fiction</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Slice of life</li>\r\n\r\n	<li>Post-Apocalyptic</li>\r\n\r\n</ul>\r\n \r\nPayment \r\nAll contributors whose work is accepted for publication your work with remain on our site permanently. In addition, contributors of stories, poems, and book reviews are paid $50 each; illustrators are paid $40 per illustration.', 'Submissions', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2107-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-26 02:15:05', '2014-10-26 02:15:05', '', 2107, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2124', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
