rk or a link to your portfolio page along with a bio letter.\r\n\r\nWould you like to illustrate your own story? It’s perfectly find to send an illustrated story by yourself or a friend. If we like the story and the illustrations, we will publish them both. If we like the story but not the illustrations, we will find our own illustrator for your story. If we like the illustrations but not the story, we will contact you to see if you’d like to become an <span class="afrikana">Afrikan Review</span> illustrator. Remember to send copies of your artwork, not originals.\r\n\r\n<h2>Poetry</h2>\r\nPlease submit 3-5 poems.\r\n\r\n<h2>Flash Fiction</h2>\r\nAll flash fiction and flash nonfiction should be under 1000 words.\r\n\r\n<h2>Prose Fiction or Nonfiction</h2>\r\nWe are looking for prose that is arresting, that fearlessly disrupts the story on black teens and children. Stories that grips our throats. Stories that break our hearts. Stories that blows our mind. We want the unexpected, prose that extends the plight of boundaries blackness in form, language, or narrative. \r\n\r\nAll other forms: No more than 2 pieces not exceeding 5,000 words or twenty pages.\r\n\r\n<h2>Graphic Novels or Comics</h2>\r\nFor this type of submission, we request that you submit in .jpg, .tiff or .pdf format.\r\nQuery before sending in book reviews, interviews, and literary criticism. (editor@afrikana.com) \r\n\r\n<h2>Do You Accept hood Literature?</h2>\r\nAlthough we read fiction of all stripes and frequently publish work that crosses or bends genre lines, we do strongly recommend that all submitters familiarize themselves with <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> before sending work.\r\n\r\n<h2>Can A Historical Figure Be a Protagonist?</h2>\r\nWhile we are not against historical figures in your stories, they just cannot be the protagonist. We are looking for fresh new protagonists that drive the story forward.\r\n\r\n<h2>Can The Protagonist Be of Mixed Race Heritage?</h2>\r\nNo, the protagonist nor the family members, if the protagonist has any family, can be racially mixed. If you are sending a illustration, the protagonist must look visibly Afrikan. When we mean “visibly Afrikan,” we mean there can be no doubt of the character''s racial makeup to <strong>our readers or us at <span class="afrikana">Afrikana</span></strong>. We will leave this up to you judge what is considered “visibly Afrikan.” Please be aware that your ideal may not be others.\r\n\r\n\r\n<h2>What If The Protagonist Is Of Another Species?</h2>\r\nIf the protagonist is of another species, that is fine, however, if the species resembles human beings (like Superman for example), they must look “visibly Afrikan.”\r\n\r\n<h2>Can The Protagonist Be From Another Country Outside The United States?</h2>\r\nYes, they can. We understand that the majority of Black teens reside outside the United States. We would love to hear stories from protagonist of different countries. Feel free to sprinkle in your native language (provided with a glossary).\r\n \r\n<h2>Payment</h2>\r\nAll contributors whose work is accepted for publication your work with remain on our site permanently. In addition, contributors of stories, poems, and book reviews are paid $50 each; illustrators are paid $40 per illustration.', 'Submissions', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2107-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-26 02:44:10', '2014-10-26 02:44:10', '', 2107, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2139', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
