(2170, 1, '2014-10-27 03:02:07', '2014-10-27 03:02:07', '<h1>The Afrikana Review Theme Issues</h1>\r\n\r\nSubmissions are accepted February 13-15th, May 13-15th, August 13-15th, and November 13-15th. We consider each submission for all upcoming issues, regardless of theme. If you wish to be considered for a particular theme, please make note in your cover letter.\r\n\r\n<blockquote><span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review </span>has announced the summer theme Fight to the Death. We are looking for fiction, essays, and poems about Fighting to the Death with people, animals, organizations, institutions, physical locations—the theme is open to interpretation. </strong></blockquote>\r\n\r\nGifted teens are <em>highly</em> encouraged to send stories, providing they are high quality.\r\n\r\nSimultaneous submissions are permitted. Please notify us immediately if the work has been accepted elsewhere. We prefer work that has not been previously published. <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> asks for non-exclusive electronic rights.\r\n\r\n<h2>Formatting</h2>\r\nFormatting Standard manuscript format is required, 12-point font (Times or Times New Roman), double-spaced with one-inch margins all around. Please put the page number, your last name, and title of entry in the top right corner of each page. Attachments are required and MUST be labeled with the title of your piece. Please send your work in a PDF. Please do not send your work in the body of your email. Send submissions to: edior@convenientstore.com. Subject line in ALL CAPS: SUBMISSION. YOU MUST INCLUDE A COVER EMAIL WITH THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: \r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A brief summary of your narrative (3 sentences) if you have one. </li>\r\n<li>A brief bio (no more than forty words, please.). </li>\r\n<li>No pieces that are previously published accepted.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n\r\nIf you would like to illustrate for <span class="afrikana">The Afrikan Review</span>, please send us three samples of your artwork or a link to your portfolio page along with a bio letter.\r\n\r\nWould you like to illustrate your own story? It’s perfectly find to send an illustrated story by yourself or a friend. If we like the story and the illustrations, we will publish them both. If we like the story but not the illustrations, we will find our own illustrator for your story. If we like the illustrations but not the story, we will contact you to see if you’d like to become an <span class="afrikana">Afrikan Review</span> illustrator. Remember to send copies of your artwork, not originals.\r\n\r\n<h2>Poetry</h2>\r\nPlease submit 3-5 poems.\r\n\r\n<h2>Flash Fiction</h2>\r\nAll flash fiction and falsh non-fiction should be under 1000 words.\r\n\r\n<h2>Prose Fiction or Nonfiction</h2>\r\nWe are looking for prose that is arresting, that fearlessly disrupts the story on black teens and children. Stories that grips our throats. Stories that break our hearts. Stories that blows our mind. We want the unexpected, prose that extends the plight of boundaries blackness in form, language, or narrative. \r\n\r\nAll other forms: No more than 2 pieces not exceeding 5,000 words or twenty pages.\r\n\r\n<h2>Graphic Novels or Comics</h2>\r\nFor this type of submission, we request that you submit in .jpg, .tiff or .pdf format.\r\nQuery before sending in book reviews, interviews, and literary criticism. (editor@afrikana.com) \r\n\r\n<h2>Do You Accept hood Literature?</h2>\r\nAlthough we read fiction of all stripes and frequently publish work that crosses or bends genre lines, we do strongly recommend that all submitters familiarize themselves with <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> before sending work.\r\n\r\n<h2>Can The Protagonist Be of Mixed Race Heritage?</h2>\r\nNo, the protagonist nor the family members, if the protagonist has any family, can be racially mixed. If you are sending a illustration, the protagonist must look visibly Afrikan. When we mean “visibly Afrikan,” we mean there can be no doubt of the character''s racial makeup to <strong>our readers or us at <span class="afrikana">Afrikana</span></strong>. We will leave this up to you judge what is considered “visibly Afrikan.” Please be aware that your ideal may not be others.\r\n\r\n<h2>What If The Protagonist Is Of Another Species?</h2>\r\nIf the protagonist is of another species, that is fine, however, if the species resembles human beings (like Superman for example), they must look “visibly Afrikan.”\r\n\r\n<h2>Can The Protagonist Be From Another Country Outside The United States?</h2>\r\nYes, they can. We understand that the majority of Black teens reside outside the United States. We would love to hear stories from protagonist of different countries. Feel free to sprinkle in your native language (provided with a glossary).\r\n \r\n<h2>Payment</h2>\r\nAll contributors whose work is accepted for publication your work with remain on our site permanently. In addition, contributors of stories, poems, and book reviews are paid $50 each; illustrators are paid $40 per illustration.', 'Submissions', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2107-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-27 03:02:07', '2014-10-27 03:02:07', '', 2107, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2170', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2172, 1, '2014-10-28 22:19:36', '2014-10-28 22:19:36', 'Prizes are awarded annually by the editors of <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span>. Winning selections are announced in the winter issue. No application form is required; winners are selected from the stories and poems published in <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> each year.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Story Award (13-16)</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review Story Award (13-16) is awarded to the story with targeting teens, ages 13-16, of any genre. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Story Award (16-19)</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review Story Award (16-19) is awarded to the story with targeting teens, ages 16-19, of any genre. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Theme Award</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Theme Award is awarded to the author whose story was the best of all the themeed stories. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review for Rising Writers Award</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review for Rising Writers is award to writers 19 and under who demonstrates the talent and drive to become the next great Black author for Young Adult. The winner will also serve on the prestigious panel of judges for The Afrikana Review Prize of 2016, bringing a critical young perspective to the evaluation process. Entrants must submit a Rising Writer Personal Profile of 700 characters. Those that do no will only be considered for the individual story award of their targeted audience.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Poetry Award</h1>\r\n>The Afrikana Review Poetry Award is awarded to the poet whose poem engages with the unfamiliar and provokes emotion. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Criticism Award</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review Non-Fiction Award is awarded to the writer whose study, evaluation, or interpretation of literature ', 'Prizes', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2152-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-28 22:19:36', '2014-10-28 22:19:36', '', 2152, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2172', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
