(2186, 1, '2014-10-28 22:59:38', '2014-10-28 22:59:38', 'Prizes are awarded annually by the editors of <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span>. Winning selections are announced in the winter issue. No application form is required; winners are selected from the stories and poems published in <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> each year.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Story Award (13-16)</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review Story Award (13-16) is awarded to the story with targeting teens, ages 13-16, of any genre. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Story Award (16-19)</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review Story Award (16-19) is awarded to the story with targeting teens, ages 16-19, of any genre. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Theme Award</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Theme Award is awarded to the author whose story was the best of all the themeed stories. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review for Rising Writers Award</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review for Rising Writers is award to writers 19 and under who demonstrates the talent and drive to become the next great Black author for Young Adult. The winner will also serve on the prestigious panel of judges for The Afrikana Review Prize of 2016, bringing a critical young perspective to the evaluation process. Entrants must submit a Rising Writer Personal Profile of 700 characters. Those that do no will only be considered for the individual story award of their targeted audience.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Poetry Award</h1>\r\n>The Afrikana Review Poetry Award is awarded to the poet whose poem engages with the unfamiliar and provokes emotion. The winner receives a $1,000 prize and a hand-crafted trophy.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Criticism Award</h1>\r\nThe Afrikana Review Non-Fiction Award is awarded to the writer whose study, evaluation, or interpretation of literature ', '<i class="prizes-icon fa fa-trophy"></i> Prizes <i class="fa fa-trophy"></i>', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2152-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-28 22:59:38', '2014-10-28 22:59:38', '', 2152, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2186', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2187, 1, '2014-10-28 23:17:49', '2014-10-28 23:17:49', '<h1>Our History</h1>\r\nIn recent years, erasure and gate-keeping Black creativity and the Black narrative in publishing has become a hot topic. Here at <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span>, we understand that both these acts are due to a lack of Black cultural institutions. The lack of cultural institution allows the Black narrative to be easily misconstrued, marginalized, replaced, and commercialized by the ruling racial class. The result leads Blacks to beg the ruling racial class, which benefit from the aforementioned acts (and created the situations for these acts to take root in the first place), for permission to create stories that reflect our true selves. A permission that will never come. And we at <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> don''t ask for permission.\r\n\r\n<h1>Our Mission</h1>\r\n<span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> is an online literary magazine that features young Black protagonists (ages of 13-19), from Black writers who are often ignored in mainstream and independent publishing. <span class="afrikana">The Afrikana Review</span> is committed to the ideal that the Black narrative is also the default and will lead to validation, racial pride, and ultimately cultural protection.\r\n\r\n<h1>Social</h1>\r\nFollow us on Twitter, Facebook, and Instagram.\r\n\r\n<h1>The Afrikana Review Store</h1>\r\nShop for The Afrikana Review cover.\r\n\r\nVisit the The Afrikana Review Store\r\n', 'About Us <i class="fa fa-adn"></i>', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2093-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-10-28 23:17:49', '2014-10-28 23:17:49', '', 2093, 'http://localhost/wordpress/?p=2187', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
